{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629155"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:03:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:03:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17257"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17257"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.05,0,0.64,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9947"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77926"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9947"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17257"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63395"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5725"},{"type":"tags","id":"10784"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23318"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23327"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77926"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAmniocentesis is a prenatal diagnostic procedure performed between 15-20 weeks of pregnancy. The procedure involves inserting a fine needle through the abdominal wall into the amniotic sac to collect fluid for testing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the diagnostic capabilities of amniocentesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Examines genetic material from placental biopsy","Analyses protein markers in maternal blood","Visualises fetal anatomy via ultrasound waves","Tests fetal cells from amniotic fluid samples","Screens fetal DNA from maternal circulation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary diagnostic capability of amniocentesis is that it \u003Cstrong\u003Etests fetal cells from amniotic fluid samples\u003C/strong\u003E. The amniotic fluid contains fetal cells that can be cultured and analysed for chromosomal abnormalities, genetic mutations, and neural tube defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExamines genetic material from placental biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes chorionic villus sampling, which samples placental tissue rather than amniotic fluid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalyses protein markers in maternal blood\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes maternal serum screening, which analyses maternal blood proteins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisualises fetal anatomy via ultrasound waves\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes ultrasound imaging, not genetic analysis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreens fetal DNA from maternal circulation\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes non-invasive prenatal testing using cell-free fetal DNA in maternal blood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAmniocentesis is typically performed between 15-20 weeks gestation. While it carries a small risk of miscarriage (0.5-1%), it provides highly accurate diagnostic information about fetal genetic status.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Amniocentesis involves sampling amniotic fluid at 15-20 weeks gestation to obtain fetal cells for genetic testing.","The main risks of amniocentesis include miscarriage (0.5-1%), infection, and leakage of amniotic fluid.","Amniocentesis can detect chromosomal abnormalities, neural tube defects, and genetic disorders with high accuracy."],"references":["Quinlan MP. Amniocentesis: Indications and Risks. Virtual Mentor. 2008;10(5):304-306. Available at: https://journalofethics.ama-assn.org/article/amniocentesis-indications-and-risks/2008-05"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63395"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17257"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63395"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:41:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:42:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9947"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77926"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null